text: I'll agree the Floyd missions were some of the hardest parts of the game. I think it had something to do with the camera perspective. Floyd's mission difficulty didn't ramp properly, but the devs were getting feedback from gamers who put their day into being great at playing a hard game (and a temp like me didn't have suggestions greenlit often). An optional training course would be a nice gesture, though. Thankfully, the controls were pretty tight, which I believe to be part of Rare's pedigree.

text:
They really nailed the dark vibe despite the cartoonish design. Well, I wrote *despite*; but really the art direction helped to add both counterweight and contrast to the rather grim tone at the same time. The style also helped to make the comic quips not feel out of place. Really good stuff. 
They later went *slightly* overboard with Conquer though

author: Matt 6418

text: This was the third game I tested while working at Nintendo, very shortly after completing work on DK64 (I love Rare, so '99 was a good summer for me). Both soundtracks were great, but I preferred JFG for its more challenging single-player gameplay (DK64's multiplayer was better, though). Plenty of variety in the characters' abilities, as well as a good mix of platforming, shooting and a dash of puzzles. I'd like to see a Jet Force Gemini sequel.
